# Say 67 — Fun counter (with Microphone + Leaderboard)

A tiny single-page site that "says" the viral number 67. Each time the page says "sixty seven" the on-screen counter increases. Reach 1,000 and you'll get a celebratory popup + confetti reward.

What's new
- Local anonymous leaderboard (keeps top times in your browser).
- Optional global anonymous leaderboard: submit times to a server endpoint and fetch global top times.
- Reward modal lets you save locally and optionally submit anonymously to a remote server.
- Leaderboard modal shows local top times and global top times (if remote configured).

How it measures a run
- A run starts when the counter goes from 0 → 1 (or after Reset).
- When you reach 1000 the UI calculates how long it took in ms and displays it.
- Local leaderboard stores entries of {timeMs, date} and sorts ascending (fastest first).

Local-only usage
- No server required. The local leaderboard stores top times in localStorage.

Global leaderboard (optional)
- The front-end supports submitting results to a remote server if you set `REMOTE_LEADERBOARD_BASE` in script.js to your backend URL.
- A minimal Node/Express example server is included below (server.js). Deploy that server (e.g., on Render, Heroku, Fly, or any Node host), then set REMOTE_LEADERBOARD_BASE to the server URL (e.g., https://your-server.example.com).
- Data submitted is minimal and anonymous: { timeMs: number, date: ISO string is added server-side }.

Minimal server example (save as server.js)
```javascript
// server.js - minimal anonymous leaderboard collector
// Node 16+ recommended. This stores leaderboard in a JSON file on disk (not suitable for large scale).
const express = require('express');
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');
const cors = require('cors');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
const DATA_FILE = path.join(__dirname, 'leaderboard.json');

const app = express();
app.use(cors());
app.use(bodyParser.json());

function loadData() {
  try {
    if (!fs.existsSync(DATA_FILE)) return [];
    const raw = fs.readFileSync(DATA_FILE, 'utf8');
    return JSON.parse(raw || '[]');
  } catch (e) {
    return [];
  }
}
function saveData(list) {
  fs.writeFileSync(DATA_FILE, JSON.stringify(list, null, 2), 'utf8');
}

app.post('/submit', (req, res) => {
  const { timeMs } = req.body;
  if (typeof timeMs !== 'number' || !isFinite(timeMs) || timeMs < 0) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'invalid timeMs' });
  }
  const list = loadData();
  const entry = { timeMs: Math.round(timeMs), date: new Date().toISOString() };
  list.push(entry);
  list.sort((a,b) => a.timeMs - b.timeMs);
  // cap stored results to 1000 entries
  saveData(list.slice(0, 1000));
  res.json({ ok: true, saved: entry });
});

app.get('/top', (req, res) => {
  const n = Math.min(100, parseInt(req.query.n || '10', 10) || 10);
  const list = loadData();
  res.json(list.slice(0, n));
});

app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Leaderboard server listening on ${PORT}`);
});
```

Notes and privacy
- Local leaderboard is fully client-side and never leaves your browser.
- Global submissions are anonymous. The server example stores only timeMs and timestamp; it does not collect IPs intentionally in the app (but standard server logs may contain IPs at the host level). If you want stricter privacy, deploy behind a privacy-preserving host or strip logs.
- This minimal server stores entries in a JSON file and is not production-grade; for production use a proper database and authentication/abuse controls.

How to enable global submissions
1. Deploy the minimal server above (server.js) to a host.
2. Set REMOTE_LEADERBOARD_BASE in script.js to your server URL (no trailing slash required). Example:
   const REMOTE_LEADERBOARD_BASE = 'https://my-67-leaderboard.example.com';
3. Reload the page. After completing a run, click "Submit Anonymously (Global)".

